    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Closed captions (CC)</strong> are synchronized text overlays on video that viewers can toggle on or off. They display dialogue, sound effects, and speaker identification for audiences who are deaf or hard of hearing, or for anyone watching in sound-off environments. Unlike open captions (burned permanently into the video), closed captions are a separate track the viewer controls.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Mute-scroll share</div>
            <div class="tms-value">85% (Facebook)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Social Media</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">View-time lift</div>
            <div class="tms-value">+12%</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">The single most under-priced tactic in video marketing is captions. Not because they help the deaf-and-hard-of-hearing viewer (they do), but because the vast majority of social video is watched on mute — and no captions means no message received.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What are closed captions?</h2>
        <p>Closed captions are a text version of the audio in a video, synchronized to the timeline and rendered on top of the video frame. Viewers can turn them on or off via a player control. Because they are stored as a separate track (SRT, VTT, or SCC file), the same video can carry multiple caption languages without re-encoding.</p>
        <p>Closed captions include more than dialogue. They also convey:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Non-speech audio</strong> — [door slams], [phone rings], [laughter]</li>
          <li><strong>Speaker identification</strong> — "Sarah: Let's talk about growth"</li>
          <li><strong>Music cues</strong> — [upbeat music plays]</li>
          <li><strong>Off-screen sounds</strong> — [siren wailing in distance]</li>
        </ul>
        <p>This is the difference between captions and subtitles: subtitles typically carry only dialogue and assume the viewer can hear the rest.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Audience reality</div>
          <p>Verizon and Publicis research found that <strong>80% of people who use captions are not deaf or hard of hearing</strong>. They are watching in bed, in offices, on commutes, or in loud environments — sound off, captions on.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why closed captions matter</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Sound-off viewing is the default.</strong> Facebook says 85% of video plays are muted; Instagram Reels defaults to sound-off in feed; LinkedIn users overwhelmingly watch on mute at work.</li>
          <li><strong>View time increases 12%.</strong> Facebook's internal data shows captioned videos are watched 12% longer than non-captioned.</li>
          <li><strong>Completion rates rise 15-25%.</strong> Multiple platform studies confirm captions increase completion rates by 15% or more.</li>
          <li><strong>SEO on YouTube.</strong> YouTube indexes caption text. A well-captioned video ranks for spoken phrases that would never be captured otherwise.</li>
          <li><strong>Accessibility compliance.</strong> WCAG 2.1 Level A requires captions on pre-recorded audio. ADA lawsuits have targeted uncaptioned marketing videos.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How closed captions are created</h2>
        <p>Three methods, in order of accuracy and cost:</p>

        <h3>1. Auto-generated (85-90% accurate)</h3>
        <p>YouTube, TikTok, Instagram, and LinkedIn generate captions automatically via speech recognition. Fast and free, but never perfect — technical terms, brand names, and non-neutral accents drop accuracy significantly.</p>

        <h3>2. Uploaded caption file (SRT/VTT)</h3>
        <p>A human transcribes the audio and uploads a caption file. This is what serious creators do. The file format looks like:</p>

        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># SRT (SubRip) caption file</span><br>
          1<br>
          00:00:00,000 <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> 00:00:03,500<br>
          Welcome to the growth playbook.<br>
          <br>
          2<br>
          00:00:03,600 <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> 00:00:07,200<br>
          [upbeat music plays]<br>
          Today we cover click-through rate.<br>
        </div>

        <h3>3. Burned-in captions</h3>
        <p>Text is rendered directly into the video pixels — not toggleable. Common on Reels, TikTok, and vertical Shorts because it survives autoplay-with-sound-off perfectly. Technically these are "open captions" but the practice is often grouped with closed captions in casual usage.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Closed vs open vs SDH captions</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Type</th><th>Rendered where</th><th>Toggle</th><th>Best for</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight">
                <td><strong>Closed captions (CC)</strong></td>
                <td>Separate track in player</td>
                <td class="cell-yes">Yes</td>
                <td>YouTube, web, streaming</td>
              </tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Open captions</strong></td><td>Burned into video pixels</td><td class="cell-no">No</td><td>Reels, TikTok, LinkedIn feed</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Subtitles</strong></td><td>Separate track</td><td class="cell-yes">Yes</td><td>Foreign-language dialogue only</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>SDH (Subtitles for Deaf/HH)</strong></td><td>Separate track</td><td class="cell-yes">Yes</td><td>Streaming platforms, includes sound cues</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Live captions</strong></td><td>Real-time overlay</td><td class="cell-yes">Yes</td><td>Livestreams, webinars, meetings</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real closed caption examples</h2>

        <h3>1. Fitness creator on Instagram</h3>
        <p>A fitness creator adds burned-in captions to every Reel. Completion rate rises from 41% to 52% within a month — measured across the last 30 pre-caption Reels versus the first 30 captioned Reels.</p>

        <h3>2. B2B SaaS on LinkedIn</h3>
        <p>A SaaS founder posts weekly video insights. First 10 without captions average 4,000 views and 8 shares. Next 10 with captions average 11,000 views and 32 shares. Same content, same channel, +40% shares — the algorithm rewards the higher watch time.</p>

        <h3>3. YouTube tutorial channel</h3>
        <p>A tutorial creator uploads accurate SRT files instead of relying on auto-captions. Impressions for long-tail spoken phrases (like "how to canonicalize a paginated set") rise noticeably in YouTube Search reports because Google indexes the caption text.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Closed captions vs open captions — which to use</h2>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Closed captions when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Publishing on YouTube, streaming platforms, or your own website</li>
              <li>Viewers need multiple language options</li>
              <li>You want caption text indexed for SEO</li>
              <li>You are producing formal or long-form content</li>
              <li>Accessibility compliance is required</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Open (burned-in) captions when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Publishing on Instagram Reels, TikTok, or LinkedIn feed</li>
              <li>You want captions guaranteed to appear (mute autoplay)</li>
              <li>The platform's CC toggle is inconsistent or off by default</li>
              <li>Design is part of the message (styled captions, kinetic type)</li>
              <li>You are cross-posting to platforms without CC support</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p>In practice, most brands do both: burn captions into short-form vertical video, and upload SRT files for long-form horizontal video.</p>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices for closed captions</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Never publish auto-captions without a review pass.</strong> Auto-generation is a starting point, not a final version. Ten minutes of editing raises accuracy from 88% to 99%+.</li>
          <li><strong>Break captions at natural phrase boundaries.</strong> A caption that ends mid-sentence with a clause hanging is harder to read at speed.</li>
          <li><strong>Keep captions on-screen 1 second per 20 characters.</strong> Roughly WCAG's recommended readable duration.</li>
          <li><strong>Position captions away from key visuals.</strong> The bottom 15% of the frame conflicts with UI overlays on TikTok and Reels. Center or upper-third is safer.</li>
          <li><strong>Include speaker labels when there are multiple speakers.</strong> Ambiguity about who said what kills comprehension.</li>
          <li><strong>Upload SRT files where the platform supports them.</strong> Uploaded captions are searchable and translatable in ways burned-in captions are not.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common trap — captions that read too fast</div>
          <p>Cramming three sentences into a two-second caption card feels efficient but tests badly with actual readers. Cap at ~40 characters per line, ~2 lines per card, ~3 seconds on-screen.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common closed caption mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Publishing auto-generated captions without review.</strong> One embarrassing brand-name error can outlive the campaign.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring non-speech audio.</strong> Deaf viewers rely on [phone rings] and [background laughter] to understand context.</li>
          <li><strong>Using tiny caption text on mobile.</strong> If it is not readable on a 6-inch screen at arm's length, redo it.</li>
          <li><strong>Only captioning some videos.</strong> Consistency signals professionalism and expected accessibility.</li>
          <li><strong>Assuming platform CC always renders.</strong> Facebook's auto-captions still fail on ad autoplay. Burn-in when the risk of missed captions is high.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)"><span class="faq-q-text">What is the difference between closed captions and subtitles?</span><span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Closed captions include dialogue plus sound effects and speaker cues, are designed for viewers who cannot hear the audio, and can be toggled on or off. Subtitles typically only include dialogue and assume the viewer can hear but does not understand the language.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)"><span class="faq-q-text">Are closed captions good for SEO?</span><span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Yes. YouTube indexes caption text and uses it for search and recommendation ranking. Uploaded SRT captions are more accurate than auto-generated ones and consistently improve organic YouTube discovery.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)"><span class="faq-q-text">How much do closed captions increase engagement?</span><span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Facebook video with captions gets on average 12% more view time. Video completion rates increase 15-25% across platforms. 85% of Facebook videos are watched on mute, so captions are the difference between silent scroll and viewer capture.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)"><span class="faq-q-text">Are auto-generated captions accurate?</span><span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>YouTube and TikTok auto-captions are 85-90% accurate for clear English speech. Accuracy drops on technical terms, proper names, and accents. Always review before publishing.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)"><span class="faq-q-text">Are closed captions legally required?</span><span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>In the US, the Americans with Disabilities Act (ADA) and 21st Century Communications Video Accessibility Act (CVAA) require captions on most commercial broadcast and streaming content. Marketing videos on social media are not legally required but strongly recommended for accessibility.</p></div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

